ObjectLogEntry.description: The ObjectLogEntry represents events that occur for various records ("objects"). The type of the event is identified by the "type" field. The ObjectLogEntry has many ObjectLogEntryItems that track additional types of events for the primary event identified by this record. For example, an ObjectLogEntry will be created for each Contact that receives an email, and there will then be ObjectLogEntryItems to track additional interactions the Contact has with the email, such as the Contact opening it, clicking a link, and so on. The "entry_items_count" field on the ObjectLogEntry identifies the number of ObjectLogEntryItems that are associated with it.

OntraportListFieldOption.description: Ontraport has a concept of a "list" data type that can be assigned to a field. The "list" data type is essentially a multi-select Enum, which means that a field can contain multiple selections out of a predefined set of options. This is in contrast to an Enum field that can only reference 1 predefined value at a time. Ontraport saves the selected options to these "list" fields as a string in the format: `/<optionId>/<optionId>/`. This makes it impossible to search efficiently, and also makes it impossible to perform complex queries like searching for records that have optionA OR optionB. The solution is to compile all options across all "list" fields within an Ontraport account into this centralized model. The primary key of this model is the ID of each option, which is possible because the ID that Ontraport assigns to each predefined "list" field option is unique for the entire account instead of just the field. Then, to make these options searchable for each record, a separate model is created for each "list" field to contain many-to-many associations between the records on the original model and the record's selected options (e.g., the values in the textual representation of the options). In short, the textual representation is inflated into records to form a proper association at the database level. These "field" models have 2 foreign fields: `optionId` which references the ID on this model, and a `recordId` field that references the ID on the original model. Altogether, this makes it possible to perform complex searches for records based on their chosen options. Furthermore, since this model contains the friendly name for each option ID, searches can also be performed based on the options's name instead of its numeric ID. This is crucial because users are only familiar with the option name, not its numeric ID. While this model can be searched directly, it is primary use-case is to join a field model to this model using its `optionId` foreign field in order to reference the name of an option.

columns.name: id
columns.description: The ID of the predefined option for the list field.

columns.name: description
columns.description: The description of the option, if available.

columns.name: fieldId
columns.description: The Ontraport ID of the field on the model that defines this option. As with the `objectId` field on this model, this is primarily for searching this model directly. When searching for the options associated with a particular record, use the field model that contains the many-to-many associations between records on the original model and their chosen options since the field models have an `optionId` foreign field referencing the id of the record on this model that represents the option.

columns.name: name
columns.description: The name of the option. This is useful because users aren't familiar with the numeric ID of each option. Typically, searches will involve the field model that contains many-to-many associations between records on the original model and their chosen options. Then, the field model can be joined to this model using its `optionId` foreign field to then reference the option's name.

Message.description: A Message represents an Email that is sent as part of a Blast (one-off send), a Sequence (autoresponder), or both. There will be ObjectLogEntry records for each Contact that the Message is sent to that represent each event the Contact made tied to the Message. Each ObjectLogEntry has many ObjectLogEntryItem records associated with it that further breakdown details about each event for the Contact. Altogether, it is possible to determine any number of metrics about the Message by analyzing the data available on the Message record itself, and its associated ObjectLogEntry records and their associated ObjectLogEntryItem records.

PropertyBuildingFeaturesOption.description: A many-to-many association between the PeterpmProperty model's records and the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model. The associations are derived from the PeterpmProperty model's building_features_options_as_text field, which contains a textual representation of all selected options as a concatenated string with custom separators. However, the textual representation makes it impossible to perform efficient searches. As a result, the building_features_options_as_text field's value is inflated into records on this model to build a proper many-to-many association at the database level. See the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model for full details, as that model is necessary to derive the name of the options referenced by the `optionId` foreign field on this model. Note that for this relationship, the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model's `objectId` field = "10001" and its `fieldId` field = "f3274". This is useful when searching the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model directly for options applicable to the PeterpmProperty model's building_features_options_as_text field, although typically you will use this model (PeterpmPropertyBuildingFeaturesOption) when querying for options since it contains the `recordId` property to understand what options a record is associated with.

columns.name: id
columns.description: The ID of the PeterpmPropertyBuildingFeaturesOption. This is generated automatically by combining the `optionId` and `recordId` values.

columns.name: optionId
columns.description: The optionId assigned by Ontraport. This references the `id` on the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model, making it possible to join this model to the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model to reference the name of the option. Users are only familiar with the option name, not its numeric ID. This ID represents a single entry in the PeterpmProperty model's building_features_options_as_text field (the text field with a serialized representation of all options associated with the record).

columns.name: recordId
columns.description: The ID of the PeterpmProperty record that the option is associated with.

This is useful when searching the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model directly for options applicable to the PeterpmJob model's noise_signs_options_as_text field, although typically you will use this model (PeterpmJobNoiseSignsOption) when querying for options since it contains the `recordId` property to understand what options a record is associated with.

columns.name: id
columns.description: The ID of the PeterpmJobNoiseSignsOption. This is generated automatically by combining the `optionId` and `recordId` values.

columns.name: optionId
columns.description: The optionId assigned by Ontraport. This references the `id` on the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model, making it possible to join this model to the PeterpmOntraportListFieldOption model to reference the name of the option. Users are only familiar with the option name, not its numeric ID. This ID represents a single entry in the PeterpmJob model's noise_signs_options_as_text field (the text field with a serialized representation of all options associated with the record).

columns.name: recordId
columns.description: The ID of the PeterpmJob record that the option is associated with.
